'''Sagae Hachimangū''' (寒河江八幡宮, Sagae Hachimangū) is a {{ill|Shinto shrine|ja|神社|qq=draft|qq=draft}} located in {{ill|Sagae, Yamagata|ja|寒河江市|lt=Sagae City|qq=draft|qq=draft}}, {{ill|Yamagata Prefecture|ja|山形県|lt=Yamagata Prefecture|qq=draft|qq=draft}}. Under the pre-modern shrine Ranking system, it was a [[Prefectural Shrine]] (Kensha), and it is currently a {{ill|Beppyo Shrine|ja|別表神社|qq=draft|qq=draft}} under the {{ill|Association of Shinto Shrines|ja|神社本庁|lt=Jinja Honchō|qq=draft|qq=draft}}. It served as the general guardian deity (sōchinju) of the {{ill|Sagae-shō|ja|寒河江荘|lt=Sagae-shō|qq=draft|qq=draft}}, and was once called “Kawanishi Chinju” (川西鎮守).

It enshrines {{ill|Emperor Ōjin|lt=Hondawake-no-Mikoto|ja|誉田別命|lt=[[Emperor Ōjin|Hondawake-no-Mikoto]]|qq=draft|qq=draft}} (Emperor Ōjin, the Hachiman deity) as its main {{ill|Saijin|ja|deity|lt=deity|qq=draft|qq=draft}} along with {{ill|Ōyamatsumi|ja|大山祇神|lt=Ōyama-tsumi no Kami|qq=draft|qq=draft}} as a subordinate deity.

== History ==
According to shrine tradition, during the {{ill|Zenkunen War|ja|前九年の役|lt=Before the Nine Years' War|qq=draft|qq=draft}} (also known as the Early Nine Years' War), {{ill|Minamoto no Yoriie|ja|源頼義|lt=Minamoto no Yoriie|qq=draft|qq=draft}} and {{ill|Minamoto no Yoshiie|ja|源義家|lt=Minamoto no Yoshiie|qq=draft|qq=draft}} prayed to the Hachiman deity for victory. After their success, in the Kanji 7 year (1093), they invited the deity from the {{ill|Iwashimizu Hachimangū|ja|男山八幡宮|lt=Otokoyama Hachiman-gū in Kyoto|qq=draft|qq=draft}} and founded the shrine at Hachimanbara (present-day Wakaba-chō and Motomachi in Sagae City).<ref>The old Hachiman Shrine no longer exists and has been replaced by Hachimanbara Daisan Park. However, the “Sagae-jō Ko-ezu” (Old Picture map of Sagae Castle) from the Tenshō era (1534 CE) includes the old shrine at Hachimanbara.</ref>

In the {{ill|Kenkyū era|ja|建久2nd year |lt=Kenkyū 2 (1191)|qq=draft|qq=draft}} of the Kamakura period, when {{ill|Ōe no Chikahiro|ja|大江親広|lt=Ōe no Chikahiro|qq=draft|qq=draft}} came to Sagae, he once again invited a divided spirit from {{ill|Tsurugaoka Hachimangū|ja|鶴岡八幡宮|lt=Tsurugaoka Hachimangū|qq=draft|qq=draft}} in Kamakura, merging it with the Hachiman deity already at Hachimanbara, and established a shrine building at its current site. It was revered as the tutelary deity (ubusunagami) of the {{ill|Ōe clan|ja|大江氏|lt=Ōe-shi (Ōe clan)|qq=draft|qq=draft}} (also known as {{ill|Sagae clan|ja|寒河江氏|lt=Sagae-shi|qq=draft|qq=draft}}). Together with {{ill|Yachi Hachimangū|ja|谷地八幡宮|lt=Yachi Hachimangū|qq=draft|qq=draft}} and {{ill|Mizonoeb Hachiman Jinja|ja|溝延八幡神社|lt=Mizone no Hachiman Jinja|qq=draft|qq=draft}}, it was called one of the “Three Hachiman Shrines of Sagae-shō” and held in high esteem by the warrior families. The current main hall (honden) was built in {{ill|Jōkyō 3|ja|貞享3rd year |lt=Jōkyō 3 (1686)|qq=draft|qq=draft}} and the worship hall (haiden) in {{ill|An’ei 4|ja|安永4th year |lt=An’ei 4 (1775)|qq=draft|qq=draft}}. In 1940 (Shōwa 15), it was elevated to prefectural shrine status.

Originally named “Hachiman Jinja,” the shrine adopted its present name “Sagae Hachimangū” when it was added to the list of Beppyo Shrines under the Jinja Honchō.

== Cultural Properties ==
[[File:SagaeHachimangu Yabusame2013.jpg|220px|thumb|Ancient-style yabusame]]

=== Prefectural Cultural Property (Craft) ===
* Tantō (short sword) inscribed as “Dewa Sagae Gassan”
*: Made during the Muromachi period.

=== Prefectural Intangible Folk Cultural Property ===
* Yabusame at Sagae Hachimangū
*: Held during the eve of the festival and the main festival, this includes ancient-style yabusame and “sakudameshi yabusame.” In ancient-style yabusame, mounted archers ride at full speed along a 150-meter course and shoot three targets. Three horses are used, and the performance divines harvest prospects. In “sakudameshi yabusame,” three horses are designated in advance as early-ripening, mid-ripening, and late-ripening rice; their finishing order predicts next year’s harvest. Sagae Hachimangū’s yabusame tradition is unique in Japan.

== annual Events ==
* January 1: Saitan-sai (New Year’s festival), Burning of old amulets
* February 11: Kigensetsu-sai & National Foundation Day Commemorative ceremony
* February (Lunisolar’s first Horse Day): Inari Jinja (subsidiary shrine) Hatsuumafestival
* April 28: Shinzan Jinja festival (subsidiary shrine), organized by local Minami-machi Shinzan Kō
* April 29: Kōsha Taisai (Spring festival)
* May 16: Itsukushima Jinja (subsidiary shrine) festival
* June 30: Chinowa-shinji, Nagoshi no Ōharae (Summer Purification)
* July 1: Water deity festival
* September 9: Yabusame Sango Hajime-sai (One-week purity retreat/misogi for Yabusame until the main festival)
* September 14: Eve of the Grand festival (Nambu district procession, ancient-style yabusame dedication)
* September 15: annual Grand festival (Honmachi district procession, sakudameshi yabusame dedication), Tōhoku’s largest mikoshi procession and festival
* September 16: Closing ceremony (End of Yabusame Sango purification)
* November 23: Niiname-sai (new harvest festival), offering of sacred rice by the parish youth mikoshi association
* December 13: Soot sweeping
* December 31: Tsugomori (year-end) Ōharae (Great Purification), Joyasai (Year-end festival), Chinka-sai (Fire-quelling ceremony)

